    "title": "Prime Numbers (Pledge of Allegiance)",
    "description": "&quot;There is nothing so powerful as truth — and often nothing so strange.&quot; Argument on the murder of Captain White (1830).\n\n&quot;He smote the rock of the national resources, and abundant streams of revenue gushed forth. He touched the dead corpse of Public Credit, and it sprung upon its feet.&quot; Speech on Hamilton (10 March 1831).\n\n&quot;The civilized world seems at last to be proceeding to the conviction of that fundamental and manifest truth, that the powers of government are but a trust, and that they cannot be lawfully exercised but for the good of the community. As knowledge is more and more extended, this conviction becomes more and more general. Knowledge, in truth, is the great sun in the firmament. Life and power are scattered with all its beams.&quot; Address on Laying the Cornerstone of the Bunker Hill Monument (1825)\n\n– Daniel Webster\n",
